-- Italian Stocks: Bulgari, Buzzi, Premafin, Fondiaria-Sai, Italcementi Move
-- B y   A d a m   E w i n g
-- 2010-11-23T16:44:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/fiat-eni-premafin-fondiaria-italian-market-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
dropped 421.24, or 2.1 percent, to 19,950.96 at the 5:30 p.m.
close in Milan, falling to the lowest level since Aug. 31.  The following were among the most active stocks today in
the Italian market. Symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM) jumped 1.6 percent to 7.45 euros,
rising for a third day. The world’s third-largest jeweler signed
a five-year strategic partnership with  Hengdeli Holdings Ltd . to
distribute its watches in China.  Buzzi Unicem SpA  (BZU IM) slipped for a second day,
dropping 3.1 percent to 7.42 euros. Italy’s second-biggest
cement maker fell after Credit Suisse Group AG cut its price
estimate to 9 euros from 10 euros, citing the domestic cement
market.  Italcementi SpA  (IT IM) fell 4.2 percent to 5.54 euros. The
country’s largest cement maker had its price estimate reduced to
5 euros from 6 euros by the broker.  Premafin Finanziaria SpA  (PF IM) and  Fondiaria-Sai SpA  (FSA
IM) dropped after both approved plans to raise capital. Premafin
slumped 1.9 percent to 83 euro cents, while Fondiaria retreated
3.4 percent to 6.11 euros, its lowest price since at least 1988.
Premafin is Fondiaria’s largest shareholder.  Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM) slumped 2.9 percent to 12.04 euros,
extending yesterday’s 4.9 percent slide. The world’s second-
biggest cable maker doesn’t intend to increase its bid for Draka
Holding NV.  To contact the reporters on this story:
 Adam Ewing  in Stockholm at 
 aewing5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 